    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-09-03T22:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-09-03T22:30:00-05:00" n="138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">790B.00/9–451: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Burma</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Key</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rangoon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-09-04T10:00:00+06:30"
                            >September 4, 1951—10 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>252. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 245,<note n="1" xml:id="d138fn1"
                        >See footnote 3, <ref target="#pg_291">p. 291</ref>.</note> and <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 213, Aug 31. <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> sent for me Sept 3 to advise that Cabinet had decided defer
                    reference <gloss target="#t_KMT1">KMT</gloss> problem <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> until after termination San Francisco Conference<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d138fn2">The San Francisco Conference, September 4–8, was held to
                        sign a multilateral peace treaty with Japan; for documentation, see <ref
                            target="#pg_1326">pp. 1326</ref> ff.</note> in order forestall any
                    possible attempt USSR del make political capital this development. He said
                        <gloss target="#t_FinMin1">FinMin</gloss> wld notify me due course before
                    action taken.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> stated <gloss target="#t_GOB1"
                        >GOB</gloss> appeal would call on <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> to
                    induce Taipei Govt to instruct its troops leave Burma and would contain
                    reference to our good offices and sincere though fruitless past efforts to
                    assist in arriving at a satisfactory solution.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> deprecated “double game” played by
                    Thai in permitting arms and supplies to be smuggled to <gloss target="#t_KMT1"
                        >KMT</gloss> in total disregard of embarrassment thereby caused <gloss
                        target="#t_GOB1">GOB</gloss> and despite assurances repeatedly given that
                    arms traffic would be stopped.</p>
                <p>In view of foregoing and the way things seem to be shaping up we feel that Dept’s
                    decision (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 213) very sound. We
                    encouraged by this further evidence that <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> and Cabinet sincerely desirous avoid causing US
                    embarrassment or playing into hands of Commie bloc.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Key</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
